{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778716388,"nonce":"00e90BfT0VRX9vFfEltbUHDydFo=","message":"**Correction on the vel-RMSE-ratio framing.**\n\nThe within-cell-RMSE / nearest-across-cell-RMSE ratio was computed across the 8 cells of this 2×2×2 matrix and the headline reported `GRU/jerk = 0.758` as the 'best ratio'. On reflection: the ratio is only meaningful when the cells being compared are **conditions intended to be distinguished** — i.e. experimental variables where between-condition variance reflects the signal we want to detect, and within-condition variance reflects replicate noise we want to suppress. In that setup, ratio \u003c 1 means replicates cluster more tightly than conditions separate, which is what we want.\n\nThe 8 cells of `efc4d68` are **loss-recipe variants** (smoothness on/off × jerk on/off × architecture), not conditions that we expected to produce distinguishable trained behaviour. The 'between-cell' distance here is driven by the loss functions producing different controllers by design, not by a controlled experimental variable. So the ratio's standard interpretation doesn't apply.\n\nThe **within-cell RMSE** value (`GRU/jerk = 0.112 m/s`, a 71% reduction vs the GRU/none baseline 0.391 m/s) is a meaningful number and stands as a reference. The **ratio** number (0.758) shouldn't be propagated as the headline.\n\nThis conflation has leaked into subsequent matrices — `f47abb1` and `2bc95fd` both anchor their threshold on the 0.758 figure, and `c99ad9d` comment #22 references it as the 'prior best'. Those framings should be re-stated in terms of within-cell RMSE (in m/s, on a comparable task config) rather than ratio.\n\nGoing forward (instruction surfaced from another session and probably should be codified in CLAUDE.md): **use a within/across ratio only when the across-axis cells are intended to be distinguished by some experimental variable**. Loss-recipe sweeps don't qualify. Variance-suppression sweeps don't qualify. Adversarial η_max sweeps don't qualify either, unless you specifically want to test whether replicates cluster tighter than η responses. For everything else, report within-cell RMSE directly.","files":null}]}